The 2019 Indian general elections took place in seven phases from April 11 to May 19, 2019. The primary contenders were the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), led by Prime Minister Narendra Modi, and the Indian National Congress (INC), led by Rahul Gandhi. The BJP secured a decisive victory, winning 303 out of 545 seats in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of India's Parliament). Narendra Modi was re-elected as Prime Minister, and the BJP-led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) retained a comfortable majority. The INC and other opposition parties faced significant setbacks, marking a significant mandate for the BJP and Modi's leadership. The elections saw a high voter turnout and were widely regarded as a reflection of the public's support for the BJP's policies and Modi's leadership
